		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Excellent [4.68]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=gbaji&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p><blockquote><b id="fs8">dbernor wrote:</b><hr size="1" />Thats exactly how I was thinking of it Jiggi, well, Like I said before...Wont know what I truely think til I see it I guess.<hr size="1" /></blockquote><br><br>The timer really wont be any restriction at all. Not in comparison to what is gained. It *only* limits you if you need to change stance twice in a 5 minutes period of time. Exactly how often is that going to happen?<br><br>Most of the time, stance changes are going to occur when your group makeup changes. That just doesn't happen that often. Once an hour or so maybe. The only time this will *ever* cause any sort of delay for anyone will be if you switch to offensive stance and then your healer immediately goes LD or something. So your group either struggles along for 5 minutes while your heals are half effective, or they *wait* for 5 minutes. So about the time the group decides that the healer isn't coming back from LD, you'll be able to switch from offensive stance to defensive and fill the healing role in the group.<br><br>I just don't see that as a huge limitation for an ability that is essentially a straight 25% increase in class capability.<br><br><br>Now if they made it a 5 minute &quot;casting time&quot; process to change, that would be another matter entirely. So you want to change stances, so you trigger the new stance and 5 minutes later it takes effect. That would actually limit the ability, but would honestly be so annoying that I'd be against doing it that way as well.<br><br>Dunno. I'm on the fence on this one. If they're revamping other classes in equivalent ways, that's fine. But from the looks of it it looks like they are just giving one of the few classes in the game that already has an amazing amount of utility and capability even *more* of that while not really increasing anyone else either. How about they address the fact that there are other classes that *right now* have a harder time getting into a group then a druid does, bring less to a group then a druid does, and *also* can't solo as well as a druid does to boot? How on earth does anyone look at that kind of imbalance in the game and conclude that the answer is to make druids *more* useful?</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8">Posting from San Diego, CA</td></tr></table>
