		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform2" valign="top" id="forumSubject">
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Thu, Mar 17th 9:15 PM2005 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class="sm">IP: Logged</span> | <a class="sm" href="/forum.html?forum=1&mid=1110913474628934961&num=66&page=1&post=1&replyto=1111112113825532416"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." height="11" width="17" /> Reply to this</a></a>    <a name=1111112113825532416></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=1286"><span id=Encyclopedia>gbaji</span></a><b><span id=Encyclopedia><br>Encyclopedia</span></b><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />9795 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Excellent [4.68]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=gbaji&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p><blockquote><b id="fs8">czaemon wrote:</b><hr size="1" /><blockquote><b id="fs8">Quote:</b><hr size="1" />How about they address the fact that there are other classes that *right now* have a harder time getting into a group then a druid does, bring less to a group then a druid does, and *also* can't solo as well as a druid does to boot?<hr size="1" /></blockquote><br>what class has a harder time getting groups than a druid?<br><br>I mean, besides berserkers, they aren't a real class anyhow.<br><br>druids, except in a place where snare is needed, are dead-last choice for most groups.&nbsp;&nbsp;<hr size="1" /></blockquote><br><br>Or any group that doesn't have a cleric. Or heck. Any group that wants a nuker.<br><br>Not dead last. Druids can fill several roles. They aren't &quot;the best&quot; at them, but they aren't a waste of a slot either. They bring snares, heals, dots, nukes, harmony, buffs, and evacs to any group.<br><br>You yourself placed druids pretty high on the dps listing Czae. Right there, that puts them ahead of everyone else on the list if the group is looking for more dps. The fact that they can also heal, and also snare, and also harmony, and also buff is just icing on the cake that makes them a bit more attractive.<br><br>Want a list of classes that aren't as desired for groups as druids? Hmmm... Paladins, Shadowknights, and warriors. Numerically, since these three classes are *only* realy useful to a group that doen't have a tank, they're going to have a hard time getting a group invite. You'll invite a druid to a group that already has a healer, because they can nuke too. You'll invite a druid to a group that already has a nuker because they can heal and buff too. You'll invite a druid to a group that already has a snarer because they can nuke, and buff, and harmony too.<br><br><br>You'll invite a warrior to a group that already has a tank because they can... Oh wait! they can't really do anything else, can they?<br><br>At least paladins and SKs have *some* utility. You'll invite a SK to a group that already has a tank if you still have a need for a snarer and/or puller (of course, you could invite a druid and get a snarer, outdoor camp breaker, and healer, and buffer and nuker. Hmmm...). You'll invite a paladin to a group that already has a tank if you need a bit more healing or buffing, or spell interruption (the only thing that a druid doesn't bring even more of to the group).<br><br>Most groups will take a druid over a wizard. Druids don't have quite as much nuke power, but they can heal, and buff, and snare, and harmony. A wizard can... well. Do moderate dps. Even if you're just looking for more spell dps, you might take a druid over a wizard (cause the smart group plans for the eventuality of their healer leaving, and why not get someone who can fill 80% of the role of *both*?).<br><br>Sure. Necros and mages are more dps then druids, but again. They *can't* buff or heal folks like a druid can. I don't think you can downplay the value that a druids flexibility brings to a group. A group with a druid in it can recover from any other single group member leaving (except tank) easier then a group that doesn't have one.<br><br>And after all. It's not like you need to have a second tank in case your current one leaves. Odds are there are a half dozen warriors, SKs, and paladins sitting in the LFG listing just waiting to get a group invite. The biggest scarcity for groups are slowers and healers, in that order. So Shamans are hugely in demand for groups. Chanters are hugely in demand for groups. Clerics are hugely in demand for groups. And druids are hugely in demand for groups. Everyone else is relatively interchangeable. Those 4 classes can pretty much get a group invite any time of the day (or at least far faster/easier then anyone else).<br><br>By my way of thinking, that puts druids ahead of 11 other classes in terms of group desirability. Funny that...<br><br><br>What's even more funny (ok. It's actually not), is the amount of attention that has been paid to those exact same four classes in relation to other classes. Clerics got a huge boost to improve their soloability (which largely means that they have these cool summoned hammers so they can dish out tons of dps while still  healing in a group). Chanters have had numerous *second looks* and tweaks in terms of charming and how it affects their ability to group and solo (to the point where a chanter in my guild prefers to charm solo in HoH over grouping for exp in WoS since he can get more exp more consistently soloing). Shamans also bitched about a lack defined role (or something. not sure), and got improved pets, vastly improved heals, and better canni abilities. Druids bitched about not being groupable enough and got vastly improved heals, better pets (ok. Not much there admittedly), and better buffs (Po9 line was a *huge* group buff improvement for druids).<br><br>During that time period what did us other classes get? Hmmm... I can't speak for other classes, but paladins got their stuns reduced in number and effectiveness (I'll be the first to admit that they were overpowered, but it's still a reduction). We got our group heals expanded, right at the time when long AE fights virtually disappeared from the game (gogo useless abilities!). Our pacify never got upgraded so it's become more useless as the level bar keeps growing. We did get a couple self buffs, but nothing stellar and nothing that increases our tanking to even near level of a warrior, or our dps to anything more then &quot;pathetic&quot;.<br><br>And now SOE is re-assessing class balance, and what are we seeing? Paladins and SKs are &quot;fine as we are&quot;, but somehow they think that druids need to have a toggle to make them 25% more effective at any given role they take on in a group? You're kidding me!<br><br><br>Again. Let me re-emphasize. I'm not taking a &quot;this sucks&quot; position on this stuff yet. We haven't seen everything they're planning yet, so any final judgement would be premature. But I will go on record as saying that if they are planning on improving druids, who need about as little improvement as any class in the game by the amount they say they are, then they'd damn well better be giving me some pretty freaking amazing new powers to even come close to balancing that out. Druids are allready 10 times more powerful and useful then my class. They solo better. They group better. They raid better. Paladins need something serious just balance out the discrepancies that exist in the game *right now*. If they're raising the bar for those classes already at/near the top, they need to do even *more* to balance things.<br><br><br>I just think they should be looking at where the problems in the game actually are and fixing those. Right now, the biggest problem in the game is the *enormous* difference in soloability generated by the past 4 expansions method of increasing the toughness of mobs by increasing their melee dps. This has created a gulf between classes that solo by getting hit and those that solo by avoiding getting hit. When my class is literally restricted to soloing mobs that a druid/necro/wizard/mage/chanter 10 levels lower then me can solo (easier and faster I might add), there is something seriously skewed with the game.<br><br>To then correct for the lack of groupability for those same classes by making them *more* desirable in groups then my class (which is bad at soloing because I'm supposed to be a &quot;group&quot; class), then there's even more imbalance. If I lose soloability because I'm supposed to be a &quot;group class&quot;, then you damn well need to make sure I'm better and more desired for grouping then a &quot;solo&quot; class.<br><br>That should really be the absolute first thing they look at here. Fix that imbalance in the game. Either decide that soloing is &quot;bad&quot;, and nerf it to heck for everyone, or decide that it's a valid alternative to grouping and make it viable and relatively even for *everyone*. What they've done is vacilate on the issue back and forth and each time they decide that soloing is ok, they give something more to the &quot;solo classes&quot;, and each time they decide the want to encourage grouping, they make solo classes more desirable to groups. At every point of the pendulum swing those same classes get improvements, while everyone else gets stuck falling farther and farther behind. <br><br>sheesh.</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8">Posting from San Diego, CA</td></tr></table>
