		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Excellent [4.68]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=gbaji&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>Sorry. I generally respect what you have to say, but either you are way out of touch, or are grouping in competely different areas then the rest of the player base groups in.<br><br><blockquote><b id="fs8">czaemon wrote:</b><hr size="1" /><br>in pickup groups, druids are last choice for everything, except maybe outdoor pulling and snares.&nbsp;&nbsp;  warriors CERTAINLY don't have a harder time getting groups than druids.<hr size="1" /></blockquote><br><br>And where are the current &quot;hot&quot; group spots? *cough* outdoor zones, chock full of mobs that run like a freaking bullet if not snared. Given a choice between ranger, SK and Druid Czae which do you think most groups will pick?<br><br>If you need a tank/puller, you'll take a SK. If you've already got one, you'll take a druid. Ranger is much more of a &quot;sixth slot if no one else is around&quot; option here. The difference between a druids track and a rangers is irrelevant in a cramped outdoor zone, and the druid brings a lot more to the group. Unless you *need* a puller, you'll take the druid.<br><br>Groups *only* take warriors if they need a tank. That's 1 slot in 6 Czae. Druids can fill like 4 different potential slots. The only thing they *can't* do is slow and tank.<br><br><blockquote><b id="fs8">Quote:</b><hr size="1" />for pickup groups, monks/bls/wizards/rogues/most other classes will all be taken over druids.<br><br>currently, many groups would rather just wait for a cleric than take a druid.<hr size="1" /></blockquote><br><br>Sure. If they already had just one cleric in the group, and that cleric just left, then the *have* to wait for another since a druid alone probably can't cut it. But in most groups, you'll do better with two druids healing (or a druid and a shaman healing) then a cleric and *any* other class. Most pickup group folks know this. Clerics are hard to find Czae. The last 3 camps I did in WoS used druids for healing. I'd say that I've probably had a druid MH for most camps I've done in the last 6 months over clerics by a factor of 3 or 4.<br><br>Sure. We'd like to take a cleric, but there's rarely enough clerics to go around, and druid is the next best healer in the game. The fact that picking up a druid now doesn't hurt you is just icing on the cake. If we pick up a druid, and then 10 minutes later a cleric shows up on LFG, we can pick up the cleric and the druid can switch to nuking. Grabbing a druid for your group is a no-lose proposition.<br><br><blockquote><b id="fs8">Quote:</b><hr size="1" />it's not that druids *can't* do a lot, or are necessarily a bad group choice, but they are rarely invited for anything except sixth slot filler.  <hr size="1" /></blockquote><br><br>I don't see that at all. Druids are the second choice for healers. They are the second choice for nukers. They are the first/second choice for snarers. In a game where these three (tank, healer, slower) are virtually required for a group to work well, druids are pretty high up there out of those first three &quot;needed&quot; slots. Additionally, they aren't pidgeonholled out of the 4th, 5th, and 6th slots due to too much single focus. Groups will hesitate to pick up a chanter if they've already got a shaman (and vice versa). Groups will hesitate to pick up a tank class if they already have a tank. That's because those classes to a great extent fill a role that only one character needs to fill in a group. But druids have the unique ability to fill one of those three roles and *also* fill in others as well. None of the other &quot;big three&quot; can say that (or at least not to the extent that the druid can).<br><br><br>I just don't agree at all. Druids have been a very powerful class for some time, and are still very powerful. There's a reason there are so many of them...</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8">Posting from San Diego, CA</td></tr></table>
